  "summary": "The narrator expresses a deep sense of foreboding and unease to Dr. Franklin. Judith emerges from the house with a serious expression, prompting Norton to compare her to the Jewish heroine who decapitated Holofernes. Judith informs the group that Mrs. Franklin has invited them to her room for coffee.\n\nThe group gathers in Mrs. Franklin's room, where she prepares coffee with the assistance of Nurse Crevlin. The attendees include Franklin, Boyd Carlington, Elizabeth Coleridge, Norton, and the narrator. While the group discusses a crossword puzzle involving clues about Tennyson and Shakespeare, Judith walks out onto the terrace. She calls out that she sees shooting stars, prompting Boyd Carlington to lead most of the group, including Mrs. Franklin, out to the balcony to make wishes.\n\nLeft alone with a newspaper, the narrator becomes overwhelmed by a memory of a tropical night and a woman named Cindy, which causes him to weep silently. To hide his distress when Judith re-enters, he pretends to be studying a book of Shakespeare. After the group disperses, Franklin expresses satisfaction with his evening and goes for a walk. The narrator later encounters Franklin and Judith in the hallway; Franklin asks Judith to walk with him, but she declines. After the narrator parts ways with Franklin, he goes to Bello's room and finds Judith. She kisses him and asks for his forgiveness regarding an incident involving \"Uncle Heracles.\"",
